segments.text: When were you first employed by NASA?
I think it was about 1962 when I started working here.
How old were you?
I was 21.
And what was your position?
I was working as a research scientist for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration and went to work in Cleveland, Ohio working on

trying to determine how it was going to go to the moon and what procedures would go up there and what type of launch vehicles it was going to use and the size of the vehicles and the procedures at which we would go about putting man on the moon.
What is your current position at NASA?
I'm currently heading up the Projects Office, Operations Office for the Space Station Project Office.
And this involves overseeing the overall space station design and making sure that all the operational considerations and how you're going to work with the station is considered into the design.
And working any design problems we have in terms of operations and generally the integration of that whole activity.
What various programs have you been involved in at NASA since you've been employed here?

I started out really in the later days in the Mercury program and went through the, totally through the Gemini program, the Apollo program, the Skylab program, the ASTP program, the Apollo Soyuz program, and of course for the last 10 years or 10 or 12 years we've been working on the space
or the SDS space transportation system and the orbiters operations and now I'm currently involved in the space station design development.
I've actually worked on all the manned, two manned flights in terms of anytime you had to rendezvous or anything like that with vehicles then I was over to all those flights.
How were our programs at NASA influenced by the desire to beat the Russians in establishing U.S. preeminence in space?
That definitely had a big push back in the early days of getting man into space because there was concern about what the Russians was going to do in space and etc.
It was a big challenge back in the early days to try to beat the Russians.
We had a really big battle trying to determine if we was going to beat them to the moon or not.
And it was never really clear when they decided not to go to the moon.
But he was definitely ahead of us in terms of unmanned activities, and we did catch up with him.
and have passed them over the last few years.

That's probably, excuse me, primarily the reason Russians got a big jump on us was that when they built the boosters and things for their ray bombs and hydrogen bombs, they didn't try to clean them up.
They had to have large launch vehicles

to make them intercontinental, and therefore that size of booster did have also the capability of achieving orbit, where in turns we had took off, took into the policy of making clean bombs, making the bombs small, taking smaller launch vehicles, and when the Russians decided to put a satellite into orbit, they had the launch vehicle to do it, and when we saw them do that,
put them ahead of us considerably.
We tried to do it, we didn't have a launch vehicle to do it, so we had to go out and build a launch vehicle from scratch.
So therefore, we was in a catch-up mode for several years.
Does Russia have a shuttle now, or where are they right now?
Or do we know?
There is some pretty good feeling, I guess, where they're at.
They've done a pretty good
feel and man presence in space, they've got their own space station.
They've been operating it for several years now, I don't know exactly how many, and they have manned it many times with various lengths of cruise stay time going up to several months at one time.
So, as far as man's presence in space and running the basic experiments and that sort of stuff, they have
That's what they've been concentrating on.
There are some feelings that they're building that also will be on the space shuttle.
It'll be a few years probably before that gets completed, but they're evidently working on that.
And what else they're doing, I'm not really too much upon that.
When you worked in Moscow guiding the Apollo-Soyuz flight in 1975, what differences did you notice between our space agency and theirs?
Are there, is their agency primary militaristic?
What did you notice?
Well, the control center is located on a military base behind armed guards, concrete walls several feet high.
That would imply it was a little more materialistic than what our program has been.
I'd say yes, it probably is in those terms.
What was the other part of that question?
I'm sorry.
What differences did you notice between our space agency and theirs?
Well, that can get into a couple of days worth of discussion in case we try to make it short.
They had a lot more control over their people, I think, than we have over ours in terms of, they didn't let the left hand know what the right hand was doing as much as we do.
In terms of the actual operations, they have, they actually have three control centers
that where we have one control center feeding information up to any particular activity on orbit.
They may have changed that over the recent years, but when we was there, that's what they had.
As far as getting down to detail, I guess what we're really talking about here is how you actually operate.
They had, the control center is remarkably laid out like ours was.
It was almost a
identical copy.
And since there's control centers built after ours, ones we worked out of, I have my own assumption there is that they copied ours.
Even all the way down to console positions actually, front row, second row, third row, fourth row, console positions.
As far as operating in the control center itself, one of the things that we've always done in our console positions is that
You could always overhear what the flight director was saying.
Most people would overhear on their comm lines what flight directors were talking to other people about.
The Russian control procedure there was to say that you had individual comm lines, so you couldn't sort of eavesdrop on what was happening.
That was a little bit more, keeping you more boxed in on what you were doing.
The state of the art of the control center was

was way, way beyond ours, or way behind ours in that they only had one computer generated display in the control center itself that we could see where we have at that time all of our displays were computer generated.
Their main way of displaying data was taking computer pronounced software computers and actually
put him on a TV camera and project him with TV cameras.

As an agent, I was talking more or less in terms of operations, and I guess we can get into more detail on that if we wanted to, but jumping there back to what was the difference in their operations and how they worked versus how we worked, there's a couple, I think, unique characteristics there.
One was
they took and they would have single objective flights.
Otherwise the B-1 do one.

I forget how many launches they made in getting prepared for the Apollo service mission, but they probably made a half a dozen launches just to check out systems and check out procedures and that sort of thing.
In fact, we didn't have any launches to get in preparation for the Paul Sawyer's flight.
But they have single objective missions, and if they achieve that objective successfully, they come back.
And if they don't, they launch again and try it again.
And where we try to pack our flights,
and considered on-orbit time is very valuable and we spend many, many hours trying to overlay the timelines so if something doesn't work, we pull up something else to try to fill in that timeline.
So maybe do you think because their government completely supports their program and we don't have quite as much, maybe we don't have as much money to spend meticulously doing that kind of thing?
I think it has a lot to do with it, yes I do.
they have, they're less accountable to the people on how they spend their military, military, excuse me, how they do their space operations and their budgets.
And they're not constrained as much as we are because we're accountable to the general public and everybody's down to one side and listens in on everything that's happening and we're constantly
covered by the news media and totally open to the public.
So, which makes us have to pack everything we can into a particular flight, which is involved and does cost a lot of money to do that.
But that's one of the main things I could see a difference in terms of all flight planning and that sort of stuff is how they worked.
But the control was basically the same as ours.
with the exception of the way they actually did the internal control at the center, and the comm lines and such stuff.

They seemed to be a little more, I don't want to say secretive, that's not necessarily the right words, but they tried to keep everybody with blinders on and looking down into certain paths and not be able to oversee.
One thing I guess I got the impression of is that

If you had an expertise in one particular field, and I had an expertise in another different field, and I was talking to a third individual who we would interface with, and if him and I would make a decision that would affect you, well I would
I would come back and call you up and say, hey look, Allison, Joe and I made this decision.
I think it's going to affect your area and etc.
You ought to be prepared for this or try to go talk to them and work it out.
And we would do that.
That's a common way we work.
I feel that the Russian system is not incentive to do that, so I wouldn't come back and call you up.
I'd let you find out yourself.
Okay, how were you treated by the Russian people overall as far as your stay?
Not necessarily the people at the station, but just the people when you were there?
I couldn't have been treated better by any group of people, either engineers working with them or also the general public.
I spent a lot of my spare time amongst the local people.
One was accepted with totally open arms.
It was really neat.
I spent many hours talking to people who knew less English than I knew Russian, and I knew about six words of Russian.
You made a lot of use of a pencil and a piece of paper.

You learn to talk with your hands a lot, and of course, unfortunately, you can only get to a certain level of understanding of each other, because we are communicating, I guess, what would a space agency call on a level A or top level of amount of communications, where you and I are conversing on a CD type level, otherwise a detail level of communications.

They were absolutely astounding people, and that at any time you had time to talk to them and discuss something with them, they was there, they would make time for you, if it's three o'clock, four o'clock, five o'clock, six o'clock in the morning.
They'd have a pot of tea on, they called it chai,
and very eager to learn about us and our ways and what we did and that sort of stuff.
So it was sort of a very interesting experience to go in and talk to those people.
It's so much different than I think the United States are.
I think they treated us a lot better than we treated them as individuals.
They weren't suspicious of you or anything like that?
No, ma'am.
Not to be sure, not really suspicious.
It was really, of course now I have to go back on the other hands too, though some people really didn't know what I was doing.

The Europeans, especially Eastern European countries and all of Russia was totally, at least the Russians, were totally behind this involvement we had in the space, where in the United States we treated it as
as hey, that's something NASA's doing and not much involvement and maybe heard about it once a month.
Well, I don't think it's a day went by that I didn't hear something about the Apollo Soyuz program on TV or on radio while I was stationed there.
They come out with all kinds of souvenirs, they even had a brand of cigarettes called Apollo Soyuz that was issued on the day of launch.
and special stamps and special plaques and they really had the people really pumped up for it.
They put a lot into it.
So therefore, that essentially is what the country was putting behind it.
This is a big thing for them and they really pushed the people for it too.
But anyhow, we had a
The excitement and the involvement I don't think was totally in my communications with some of the Russian people.
Their openness and friendliness towards me had really, I don't think, that much to do with what I was doing.

How did your impressions and attitudes toward the Russians change from the time, you know, what were your attitudes before you went, and then what did you come back, you know, feeling for the Russians?

I tell anybody that's traveling to Russia the first time, second time, third time, let me tell you my fourth trip to really start understanding the Russian system, and the first time you go there, your basic travel people or travel bureau's interest, interest will show you some neat things and show you a lot of history, and naturally it'll give you the best propaganda.
and keep you busy enough that you don't.
Now I wasn't, don't get me wrong, I wasn't with interest, but you sort of got effectively the same treatment.
That you get so involved in what's going on that you don't really have time to look around and see what's really happening around you.
And it's only after about the third or fourth trip or encounter that you really start getting the total feel of the impression of the people.
the constraints on the society, and what you're really constrained with.
For example, you can't go outside of Moscow without a permit.
Two years before I was there, you couldn't go outside your block area, your two or three block area that you're living in, after 10 o'clock at night, and if you did, you lost your job.
What happens?
You lose your job, you don't eat.
all the jobs are controlled by the government, so you have to be approved by the government to get the job.
If you don't have a job permit, you can't get it.
If you don't get it, you can't eat.
So it's quite a drastic effect on you.
Your movement is very constrained and etc., so you have no cars.
You don't?
No cars.
They do have the world's greatest transport system for people, though.
They have a fantastic
system for public transport.
And the combination of the subways and their trains and their buses and everything like that is, I don't, I haven't seen anything equal in the world.
You were talking about the permits you had to get to leave Moscow.
What did that require doing?
Well, we didn't, actually I was constrained to the Moscow region, so anything, we did take some bus trips outside of Moscow.
But I'm talking about the people who live there.
Like, for example, if you was a Russian, you would have had to go down to the local office and got a permit to come here to see me today for Brian.
You couldn't do that.
You had to state your business.
You had to state your locality.
So for you to travel outside of your area, region, like, say, Brian, Texas, you would have to go down and apply for a permit to leave.
and have to carry your papers with you.
It's sort of like, it's sort of equivalent to our probation system, where you, after you once get on probation, you can't leave the county without a county permission.
And if you get picked up someplace else, you wasn't supposed to be there, then you can be put in jail.
So I guess they have very little knowledge of what's going on outside.
Well, I think they get more knowledge than maybe we'll give them credit for, because of grapevine.
I'm just talking about the constraints on your freedom of travel.
and the controls are put on you.
And they spend more time there probably checking on each other than they do doing meaningful work.
So you never know who's gonna be checking on who.
So they have a lot of people looking over your shoulder and you don't know who's gonna turn you in.
You don't know who the KGB necessarily is.
So there's a lot of concern there as far as
reporting and activities you're doing.
What's your overall impression of them?
Like myself, I think of Russians as not necessarily looking like us, or I think of them as mean and out to get us and things like that.
What is your overall impression after being there of them?
I like them.
I like them in the sense that they're very humane.
We've got propaganda.
We were proprianderized every day, every time we turned the radio on.
We were bombarded.
Unfortunately, we were bombarded so much we're into the point of being complacent as far as I'm concerned.
We don't understand the true fear of problems like somebody invading our country.
The Russians suffered a lot over the many, many years.
If you know your Russian history, I don't know that much, but we never have been invaded.
They were invaded many times.
The people themselves, they're neat.
They're as neat as any other person you met.
And one interesting thing about Russia is you didn't have to go to Florida to find somebody who spoke fluent English.
Walking down the street in a building or wherever, you'd always find people who spoke good English.
There's probably those who didn't say they spoke good English who did also speak good English.
So there is somewhat concern there of, they think we're the oppressors, we're the aggressors.
I'll give you, guess the best example I can give you.
I was on an interview or on a tour to the,
what I guess you'd call the Greek Orthodox Church.
Church is equivalent to the Vatican of Russia.
I think there's like 13 nations that makes up Russia totally.
I've sort of forgotten how many.
I think it's around 13.
Many nations make up Russia.
It's got a big language integration problem, the overall nation itself.
Even though it is huge, it's more than one language, et cetera.
Greek Orthodox Church is the main church there.
We took a tour of their facilities, equivalent to the Vatican, and had an excellent reception.
And after many glasses of champagne, vodka, cognac, et cetera, and a fantastic meal, and went through it and showed us through the facilities.
And the
the head person, the orthodox minister, the head man, I went up and talked to him as I was leaving, departing his company.
And he held my hand and he says, I wish you'd go back and tell your people that not to be so aggressive.
And now these people, see,
if you believe in the Bible and believe in the church and all that sort of stuff.
And here he's dedicated his whole life to doing that.
And they're not supposed to be controlled by the government.
Okay, they are to a certain extent, but they sort of, they don't, they back off of them for it, I can tell a little bit anyhow.
Just to say something like that gives you the overall general opinion is that we're looked at as
We look to them like bad guys sometimes, too, I think.
Of course, that's true, obviously, because they do a lot of propaganda and say, hey, UAS is bad, and all that sort of stuff.
Yeah, boy, they really do bad.
In fact, an interesting comment Jared made to you is that, to fill that thought in, was that they take and daily go through the Western paper headlines and pick out the headlines

liners of all the papers, and construct a paper, like a western, I got some copies, you know, like a western paper, and it has, you know, headlines like, three people murdered last night in New York, five people raped in Los Angeles, and 15 banks robbed, and so on and so forth.
No good news.
Just go through and pick out that, and that's what they say, that's a daily paper.
and it's really disgusting to read all that.
After you get over and read this, you say, God, the whole Western world has gone nuts.

So anyhow, there's, I think one thing you have to remember is I think the Communist Party is only equivalent to about 5% of the makeup of the Russian people, so they keep a pretty big thumb on the people, so that the majority of the people are not the Communists.
which surprised me.
It's a small percentage, I don't know if 5% is right or not.
Go ahead.
Well you're currently working on the proposed space station you were talking about and what will that station be used for and its cost to us and its benefits to society?
Can you describe that a little bit?
That's a big piece to talk about Tara.
It's obviously the next step into our manned presence of space.
It's, I think, a very logical step.
And that will establish a platform facility that will be manned.
Hopefully, we're looking at having it permanently manned.
Although, we're looking at an interim space of time where we might do a man-tended option, as we call it now.
where you just go up and man it from time to time.
We might not even take that option, but we're going to go into, I say, a total manned environment, working probably from six to eight crewmen to start with.
Is it similar to like what Russia has?
No, it's going to be a lot more sophisticated than what they have currently in orbit.
It will be permanently manned.
We'll be making round trips up there.
Right now, that has to be determined, but we'll be going up probably to the station every 30 days to every 90 days, somewhere in that frequency.
We'll be manufacturing all kinds of goods at the station.
We cannot manufacture here on Earth, especially on an economical basis, because for those manufacturing processes, it requires no gravity, a high degree of vacuum,
weightless, well, the weightlessness of gravity goes together.
Minimum amount of contaminations and will allow making better transistors, for example.
There's medicines that they can make on orbit that is uneconomically feasible to make them on Earth.
And it'll basically be a

moving towards commercial land, ground observations, mineral research into various mineral locations around the earth as far as observations from these facilities and studying other planets and that sort of stuff from the observatory position.
We'll be
probably be just as shattering on our society as the other, as the current program has had up to date.
What about the cost?
It's going to be, I mean the development cost to put the vehicle up, I mean the station up, it's going to be expensive, but it depends on how you measure expense.
Right now we're
trying to design to a station that we can deliver to the Cape to the launch facility for $8 billion.
That doesn't include launches, to put it in orbit.
Along with that, the Europeans, or the international involvement, are talking up to contributing as much as the equivalent of $4 billion.
So that would make it something like an integrated program of $12 billion.
And that's the going in price side.
We may have to take some shortcuts to meet those costs.
How large are we talking about a station?
How large would it be?
Good question.
I don't have the exact dimensions down.
We're talking about like
four habitat modules, or four modules sort of interconnected together that would be working positions and sleeping quarters and that sort of stuff for initially like six crew people.
I think the total configuration of the station weighs somewhere between 300 and 400,000 pounds.
So, the orbiter weighs 240,000 pounds.
So,
In gross wage, you're looking at something that a neighborhood weighs as much as two water chairs or less.
Which will have large solar panels and that sort of stuff on this facility.

Another big pro- one of the major things and one of the projects that functions in my office is to make people realize is that we're going to be operating this thing for the next 20 to 30 years up there.
So everything we put on it, we have to be able to repair it in space.
We had to have places to store spare parts.
We had a big logistics problem of getting supplies up and returning supplies down, and that sort of thing.
So it's going to be pretty much a manned facility, just like a place up in Greenland or something like that, and you're having to go provide supplies and things to it.
When is, what are they thinking about, or is it in the planning stages, or are we near ready to take a, you know, start on that?
We're currently in a position, we've gone through the phase A studies.
Let me try to explain to you how we go through basic programs with NASA.
We'll go through a phase A conceptual idea, like, almost to the point like, hey, there will be a space station.
Then you go through the second phase of design, phase B.
Yes, there will be a space station, and this is what it looks like, and this is what it contains.
And that's basically all on paper.
And then there's what we call the phase C and D, or C slash D. And phase C is where you actually build it.
You cut the hardware, start manufacturing.
And D is where you go into operation and those sort of go together, those two stations.
We're currently in phase B, starting phase B April 1st this year.

And we're currently, the total program is going to select eight major contractors divided between four centers around the United States to come up with the basic design within, currently shooting for 21 months.
to be done with that.
Well, you were talking earlier about other countries and contributions.
You are part of a six-member panel that's meeting in Washington to discuss what those contributions will be.
What countries are we talking about?
What contributions?
And is Russia among those countries?
Okay, number one, Russia is not among those countries.
We're talking basically for the European
nations, Western nations.
The, currently three groups of people have expressed a desire to join us into this activity.
One is ESA from Europe, which is the European Space Agency.
I believe it's made up of like 10 countries, totally sort of conglomeration of people who have joined us, and we've just got two going through one session, a successful venture with them.
and that's the space lab.
They built the space lab for us, and they build and we fly it.
Now, the Jap- and they're talking about a significant piece of the operation getting involved in terms of money's concerned.
Japanese are interested and they're wanting to get involved, and the Canadians are interested, and we've done one also interesting operation with Canadians.
with the arm, with a remote manipulator system.
So, currently we have those three.
What we're trying to do in this committee is try to give the negotiators some idea of what would be logical to let the Europeans or these international involvement do and what is not logical to do.
So what we're trying to do is to break that down and one of the big problems is that we need to figure out, they can't just contribute dollars, they gotta contribute goods.
So it's like a bartering system.
So when we define an activity that they could do, we also need to try to cost that activity, try to come up with some idea of what the equivalent dollar cost is
for that particular function.
I guess it's similar to like your, say your car.
If you let some facility change the oil in it, it'd be like a European country.
And you know what basically that dollar cost is.
You know the cost of oil, you know the cost of, you know what it costs to do the change out.
And say, well, we'd give them the job of
change no oil in your car for the next twenty years.
That's pretty straightforward.
Why isn't Russia being, they're not expressed interest or is it just that we don't really want their help in this or don't want to consider Eastern European countries?
They haven't.
I don't know the total details of that.
Obviously we wouldn't be asking them to, I think, join us into this venture.
We might share some joint activities later, but I think it's too much involved and too much technology involved here.
We want to watch the technology transfer we have between nations and very definitely we will be doing some state-of-the-art stuff.
when we're building this facility.
So their involvement might be in terms of actually coming and visiting this station at some time with other vehicles or something like that.
Or we might run some joint experiments together.
And generally those things have worked out as we sort of go the line between the western and eastern countries.
Recently the government bought the Columbia into its first top secret military flight.
Press reports said that
that the cargo was a spy satellite used for listening in on the Russians.
Do you feel that the government's goal, our government's goal in space has been shifted from exploratory to military aims?
No, I don't think so.
The military has always been somewhat, has been interested in the orbiter, in the orbiter program, and they're a customer for us to fly, and
We charge them so much per flight to make those flights and they're just like any other customer.
What administrations would you describe as being more military oriented?
Speaking of those from say John F. Kennedy to Reagan.
Well Reagan's obviously I think the more, he's more interested in the military than
Probably the rest of the presidents and probably the rest of them combined.
There's an interesting balance there, I guess, between what you do and how you operate.
But definitely Reagan has been very high on the military and what it does.
I think the rest of the presidents, I'd rate them about equal.
I can't see.
I can't see, I can't think of anything that would really pull one out above the other one right now.
Are the programs, you being a part of NASA, the ones you're working on, are they primary research oriented or are they having some kind of military applications being thought about?
Most of the programs we work on is more in the research and working
with customer requirements.
For example, the evolution of the overall space program has gone from putting man in space, to putting man on the moon, to doing, that was basically just doing tasks.
And at that time we really wasn't worried too much about customer requirements.
And then when we started in the skylight program, we started to get a little more
interested in what can we do for the customer.
There's more than one just, hey, go do the task.
It's like climbing a mountain.
After you climb the mountain, what do you do when you get there?
So in the Skylab program, we started looking for customers and doing some customer interface, more so than we'd done in the past.
And you're seeing a steady trend of that now as we move on into the Space Transportation System program, which is the orbiter.
We moved in, that's going to be pretty well totally commercialized and be, tend to go more in the commercial world.
And I guess what I'm trying to say to answer that question is that we're really going more commercial all the time and trying to satisfy as usual requirements because we're paying bucks to fly.
In the past, NASA's been dependent on congressional appropriations for money.
Is there a chance that maybe, you know, this trend toward commercialism, is there a chance that maybe in the future NASA won't be dependent upon that money?
NASA will always be dependent upon money, but you've got to consider what NASA has used for you.
NASA's used to do advanced research and development.
As you get stuff operational, then it'll be converted over to commercial use.

For example, we're going through a major contract right now, a change, coming up this fall, where we're going to contract most of the activities associated, operations activities associated with the space, with the Orbiture, to contractors.

We're going to turn this whole facility, those buildings over there, they get turned over to, they don't occupy those buildings, but the tasks that those buildings are doing gets turned over to contractors who as

hate by other government agencies who wants to fly on the orbiter, and the commercial people who want to fly on the orbiter, they pay hard dollars, and that becomes similar to how we subsidize the airlines.
First, you know, FACA, which was the old, old NASA, developed the aircraft, everything worked out, and they then started converting the aircraft, turning the aircraft over to commercial
commercial people and that's how the airline industry got started.
Or this is the start of the space industry.
What effect has the military's recent involvement in space have on future non-militaristic flights?
Are you considering the military just a customer or are they actually having an input on scheduling and
what you're carrying and anything like that?
They are basically customers.
They compete for flight schedules, flights for the vehicles.
And if they buy the total vehicle, they get dedicated flights.
And if they buy partial loads, they get integrated flights.
And I look at them as being just competition.
are users of the system, and we provide them the capability to do those particular activities.
When we went to the moon, a plaque was left behind that said, Here men from the planet Earth first set foot on the moon July 1969 A.D. We came in peace for all mankind.
Do you think that we, being Americans, are still in space for peaceful reasons?
I would think so.
I don't hear any reasons for it or not.
Of course, I'm not into all the military stuff, and even if I was, I probably couldn't say much about it.
Do you feel that space will be the next location for a military arms buildup?
It has definitely the potential of being that.
As a militaristic person, it has definite advantages.
So you do think it will be?
I didn't say I didn't think it would be, but if I had something to do in those terms, I would look in that direction for sure.
It makes things a lot simpler.

I guess what's made me ask that question is Reagan's influence on, you know, that he keeps denying, you know, about Star Wars, you know, accusations that he's working towards having Star Wars, you know, but he's at the same time wanting to put satellites up that, you know, are listening in on the Russians and stuff.
and defense weapons up there.
Well, it depends on the national policy and how you go, but space definitely offers some inherent advantages to, in a militaristic sense.
I mean, this talks about having hydrogen bomb powered lasers
